{"questionId":"9068321","questionHtml":"<p><span class=\"fontstyle0\">Outline the significance of the value of the Michaelis constant, </span><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>K</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi></msub></math><span class=\"fontstyle0\">.</span></p>","markschemeHtml":"<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>K</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi></msub></math> is an inverse measure of affinity of <span style=\"text-decoration:underline;\">substrate</span> for enzyme<br><em><strong>OR</strong></em><br>higher <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>K</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi></msub></math> indicates higher <span style=\"text-decoration:underline;\">substrate</span> concentration is needed for enzyme saturation<br><em><strong>OR</strong></em><br>low value of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>K</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi></msub></math>&nbsp;means reaction is fast at low <span style=\"text-decoration:underline;\">substrate</span> concentration ✔</p>\n<p><br><em>Idea of “inverse relationship” must be conveyed.</em></p>","meta":{"questionId":"9068321","referenceCode":"20N.3.hl.TZ0.10b(ii)","subjectId":"45-dp-chemistry-last-assessment-2024","title":"Outline the significance of the value of the Michaelis constant, Km.","paper":"3","level":"hl","questionNumber":"b(ii)","marksAvailable":"[Maximum mark: 1]","breadcrumbLabels":["Options","Options","B: Biochemistry","B.7 Proteins and enzymes (HL only)","Options","B: Biochemistry"],"memberSectionIds":[],"sectionOrders":{}}}